column168: On 8/9/2018 this shipment was discovered as containing hidden dangerous goods during the physical inspection at the DHL Express MXG service center located at 9 Otis Street, Westborough,  MA  01581. Transportation by road has been confirmed.

On 8/10/18 at approximately 0930 on arrival of flight 1227, a crew chief discovered a bag in the forward compartment that was leaking onto the belly of the aircraft.  He could smell that it was bleach.  Contract Maintenance was called and they cleaned the spill and inspected aircraft.  All was logged into log book.  The bag was a black duffle bag. After offloading of leaking bag it was discovered to have additional dangerous goods inside- lysol, a total of 3 containers of bleach, oxyclean maxforce and laundry detergent.   Spill was approximately 1 pint.  The passenger record locator is CGVRLH.  The bag originated in Orlando and connected through Charlotte.

column162: SENIOR VICE PRESIDENT OF TRANSPORTAITON COMPLIANCE
column168: Employee was loading drum of waste on to the liftgate of his truck. While removing drum from two wheeled cart on to liftgate deck, drum slipped on surface which was wet due to recent rains. Drum landed in it's side, with the closure striking the deck. The closure was not sufficiently torqued, and opened up allowing approximately 1 gallon of waste to leak from the drum. Employee was already wearing proper PPE, so drum was stood back up, and the waste was cleaned up. The lid was reset on the drum, the closure properly torqued, and then continued on to it's final destination. Due to the minimal amount spilled, no state notification was needed.
column169: Employee was terminated due to multiple infractions of health and safety. Other branch employees were retrained on the proper closing techniques for the drums we use to transport this type of waste.

column168: At 1715 hours, The Brewster Yard Car Inspector noticed wetness on both sides of  tank car GATX 212956 and reported it to the Brewster Yard Master.  The Yardmaster called  myself, John Vergis, Environmental Officer for WLE.  I came out to look at the car and found that  Crude Oil was leaking from around the Manway Lid.  Part of the gasket was hanging out from the lid.  I took Seal number 0043407 off of the lid and opened the lid.  I found the gasket to be deteriorated.   I replaced the gasket and secured the lid and installed new seal number 971784.  I then wiped down  the sides of the car and released it for service.  NARRI:5(5+5)X2=100         Cause Code:  209

column168: The shipment was being moved from the DG area to the build up area. The forklift driver in error punctured the drums with the forklift blades when trying to lift the skid on which the drums were on. He immediately realized what happened and got assistance to turn the drums upside down to prevent spillage. The substance was thick and therefore did not leak out of the drums.  The employee in question was spoken to about taking his time with delicate shipments such as drums. His quick re-action did prevent spillage.
column169: In speaking to the shipper, we suggested that such shipments should be packaged in a way to better secure the drums being shipped on a skid.  Such as padding and absorbent materials should be used.

column168: At 1930 ERTS was contacted by Myrna Reyna of XPO Logistics LLA about a cargo release. It was reported that due to a Manufacture defect approximately 6 ounces of Lemon Oil UN1993,3,III released from a 30 gal metal drum. The caller stated that the released product was contained to the trailer. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and she felt comfortable cleaning the release with granular absorbents and the proper PPE. The released product and 30 gal metal drum will be placed in a 55 gal metal drum. There were no drains, soils or waterways reported to have been impacted by the release. There is no further cleanup needed.

At 0506 ERTS was contacted by Dale Duke of XPO Logistics NNA about a cargo release. It was reported that due to a Forklift accident approximately 2 gal of UN3266,8,II Nu-brite condenser coil cleaner released from a (2) 1 gal plastic jugs. The caller stated that the released product was contained to the trailer. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and it was determined a contractor needed to be sent due to the high reactivity and extent of spill. Contractor completed cleanup and neutralized the impacted area. All waste was overpacked into a 55 gallon poly drum. Tennessee report #2284. NRC report # 1221211. No further cleanup is required.

column168: Univar's driver was making a delivery of three products to a customer using a multi-compartment trailer.   The first product was delivered without issue. During delivery of the second product (Acetone), the customer's high level alarm on their underground storage tank (UST) activated.  Customer was removing product from their UST and instructed Univar's driver to continue offloading.  The high level alarm activated a second time.  A short time later, it was discovered that the UST overflowed.  Customer cleaned up released acetone.  When preparing to make start the delivery of the third product (Toluene), Univar's driver failed to ensure the internal and external valves were closed before removing the end cap.  Product spilled out of the end of the delivery piping on the trailer.  Driver reached up to close the internal and external valve handles at which time the product stopped flowing out of the delivery piping.

column168: Employee was pumping windshield washer fluid from a tote in the back of a box truck into a customer's tank. The first tote emptied before the tank was full, so employee shut down the pumping system and switched to a new tote. When the employee restarted the pump, and opened the fill valve on the handle, the air in the line caused the hose to jump. The employee did not have a tight enough grip on the handle, which caused the handle to slip out of his hand. Approximately 1 gallon of product spilled on to the concrete floor of the customer. The employee was already wearing the proper PPE, so employee cleaned up the spill with absorbent pads. The pads were containerized in the truck and transported for disposal. No state report was made due to release not meeting state reporting criteria.
column169: Employee has been retrained on keep a frim hold on handle as air in the system may cause the hose to jump. New fill level criteria has been established by the branch to minimize switching totes in the middle of the delivery process at a customer.

Caller stated while unloading trailer a trailer at their dock they discovered (1) cylinder containing UN1977, Nitrogen, refrigerated liquid (cryogenic liquid), 2.2, with no packing group. Contractors stated the cylinder is still leaking at this time and they were not able to stop the leak due to the leak coming from inside the cylinder. column168: During routine facility inspections, personnel identified a compromised container. A courtesy report to Washington Department of Ecology was submitted and state report number 683284 was generated.
column169: The generator was informed of the faulty closure and the importance of container selection was reiterated to prevent recurrence.

column168: While performing a routine load check at the end of the days run, the driver identified a release in his trailer. An internal emergency response team was dispatched to respond. In personal protective equipment, approved by the health and safety department, the response team was successful in over-packing the leaking container into a UN rated salvage drum and in remediation of the trailer and site. The release was contained to the transport trailer with minimal impact to the parking lot asphalt. No land, soil, water ways or storm drains were impacted by this release. The container was sent to its final destination without further incident. A courtesy call to Ed Costamarius of the Utah Department of Ecology was reported. No state report number was generated due to the release being below reportable quantity thresholds.

column168: HERCULES LEASE DRIVER LEON OLIVER DROVE ONTO RAILROAD TRACK IN PATH OF ONCOMING TRAIN. HE STATED THE LIGHTS WERE NOT FLASHING WHEN HE ENTERED THE TRACK AND THE CROSSING ARMS WERE UP. HE OBSERVED THE TRAIN APPROACHING AND DETERMINED HE COULD NOT CLEAR THE TRACK. HIS TRUCK WAS ON THE TRACK, BUT THE MC331 TRAILER WAS NOT. HE EXITED HIS TRUCK PRIOR TO COLLISION. THE TRAIN STRUCK THE TRUCK AND PUSHED IT OFF THE TRACKS. THE TRAILER WAS NOT STRUCK.  THE FORCE CAUSED THE MC331 TO ROLL ONTO IT'S SIDE. THERE WERE NO INJURIES AND NO RELEASE OF PRODUCT. LA STATE POLICE HAZMAT WAS CONTACTED AND THEY SUPERVISED THE INCIDENT INVESTIGATION. THE IMMEDIATE  AREA WAS SHUT DOWN AS A PRECAUTION FOR APPROXIMATELY 8 HOURS WHILE OFF-LOADING OF THE PRODUCT TO ANOTHER TRAILER WAS COMPLETED AND THE SCENE CLEARED.  **(q#1)- IF I CHOSE INITIAL REPORT, IT APPARENTLY ASSUMES THERE IS A RELEASE AND YOU ARE UNABLE TO CHECK NO RELEASE ON Q#30.  THE FORM WOULD NOT TAKE ENTIRE SERIAL # FOR TRAILER-THE FIRST DIGIT SHOULD BE A"4". SERIAL #(4HUTA4424PG120285) (#32)- TOTAL DAMAGE AND RESPONSE COSTS NOT AVAILABLE AT TIME OF THIS REPORT.  UNION PACIFIC RR FILED INITIAL REPORT.

column168: On 08/142018 at 1535 hours EST Specialized Professional Services Inc (SPSI, CSXT Contractor) personnel in the Gentilly Yard (New Orleans, LA) discovered CHVX299017, a residue tank car of Cyclohexane leaking from top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Kraton Polymers LCC was notified. Specialized Professional Services Inc (SPSI), a CSXT response contractor, found the vacuum relief valve to be leaking. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Kraton Polymers LLC (Debbie Busken 904-307-8977). SPSI flared the car down to 0 PSI pressure, removed the defective vacuum relief valve, and installed a plug securing the release.  The car owner/ consignee Chevron applied for an OTMA and the car was moved to a shop.  The car was released under OTMA movement approval.    NAR Cause Code: 662 – Other (Describe Leak) Vacuum Relief Valve failure; Valve on valve pressure plate mount  2(4+3+0) x (2+0) = 28 NARRI   New Orleans, LA – 08/14/18 –CHVX299017 – Cyclohexane  NRC Report number: 1221535
column169: A 7.1 was filed against the qualifying shop and defective valve was removed and mailed to the car owner, Chevron, at their request.  (NAR Code: 662)

column168: On 08/24/2018 at 1925 hours EST CSXT personnel in the Gentilly Yard (New Orleans, LA) discovered TILX293148, a loaded tank car of Hexamethylenediamine leaking from top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Invista was notified. Specialized Professional Services Inc (SPSI), a CSXT response contractor, responded and found the heater coil pipe to be leaking liquid product with a PH of 14 from the inside of the heater coil pipe located in the valve box. This pipe heats the liquid line valve and goes into the pressure plate into the tank. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Invista (Derek Cargile 316-828-8483). SPSI relieved the pressure on the car and installed a temporary plug into the heater coil pipe securing the release.  The car is on hold pending repairs coordinated by the shipper.    NAR Cause Code: 630 – Heather Coils- Damaged Coils  2(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 32 NARRI   New Orleans, LA – 08/24/18 –TILX293148 – Hexamethylenediamine  NRC report number 1222624

The terminal personnel couldnot find any damage to the tote or where the tote was leaking from. At 0025 the contractors dispatched arrived on sit to the terminal. It was confirmed the amount and product released were correct. Under State Police supervision.  At 0230 ET, the contractors conducted a tote transfer.  At 0315 ET, contractors were done cleaning and containerizing the waste. (1) 55-gallon poly drum of spent absorbents and PPE was generated and (1) 95-gallon poly drum containing the cut up tote was generated, but were left on site for the terminal personnel to manage.

On August 24, 2016 at 1403 ET, ERTS received a call from Trimac personnel to report a spill of an unknown amount of UN2078 "Luprantr T80 Type 2 Isocyanate". It as stated the release was from a tanker truck due to a valve issue and impacted the asphalt below it. Contractors arrived on site at 1555 ET and stated the release had stopped. The contractor tightened the rear valve bolts to prevent further leaking. It was confirmed on August 28, 2018 at 1052 ET, that the tanker had been offloaded and was at its home terminal.

column168: During loading operations at the origin terminal, a drum was punctured by a forklift fork when moving a skid on the dock. The drum was immediately turned onto it's side to reduce further release. The released material was contained using absorbent material. The damaged drum and absorbed material were placed into an overpack for later disposal. Due to the hazard of material the package specifications were unable to be obtained.
column169: This incident may have been prevented had the forklift operator been more aware of their fork location when loading freight. The forklift operator was counselled per company policy. This incident may be used as an example of the importance of proper freight handling.

I INQUIRED AS TO HOW THE PACKAGE WAS MOVED TO ITS CURRENT POSITION. I WAS TOLD THAT JIM HOWZER HAD INSTRUCTED A SUPERVISOR TO PLACE IT IN THE TOTE AND THEN MOVE IT EVEN THOUGH THEY KNEW IT WAS A HAZMAT THAT WAS LEAKING. I PULLED OUT MY LEAKING PACKAGE DECISION TREE AND WENT TO THE PAGE FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS. I THEN PRECEDED TO PLACE THE PACKAGE IN A SPILL TUB AND CLEAN UP THE MESS. ONCE THE CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETED, I HEADED BACK TO THE PSC CAGE FOR PROCESSING.

column168: On 08/16/2018 At 2208 EST, ERTS received a call from XPO Logistics's Greg Gaines, who reported that at terminal XCN located at 5289 Duff Dr., West Chester, OH 45246-1330, a 4-gallon metal pail of UN1263 Premium White Pearl Top was crushed by freight loaded on top of it releasing 1 gallon to the floor of trailer # 3154992.  No soil, storm drains, or waterways were impacted by this release.  After reviewing the SDS with terminal personnel, they determined that they're capable of cleaning the spill and will containerize all waste in a 5-gal metal pail. There is no further cleanup required.

column168: On August 1, 2018, Dohrn Transfer Dohrn Transfer notified ERTS in regards to a hazardous, UN3266 Sodium Hydroxide release. According to the caller, the driver of a tractor trailer discovered a release coming from the nose of the trailer at a customer location. There is a small amount that has been released to the ground and inside the trailer. It is unknown in the amount released at this time. Contractor indicated that approximately 12-gallons of product has been released. Contractor indicated that approximately 2-gallons of product has been released to the ground below the trailer. Contractor neutralized the release. Contractor 1-95 Gal Poly Drum containing the overpacked / damaged drum and (2) 55 Gallon Poly Drums of Impacted absorbents and debris generated from this incident.

The trailer was about to close out when a smell was noticed. Safety and Security was called and a Haz Mat team was sent out. Upon their investigation it was determined that the drum was not punctured by a forklift but instead had a tiny hole on the side at the bottom of the drum that spilled about a cup of liquid out.
column169: Appears to be drum issue from manufacture. Proper block and brace with dunnage protection.

column168: On 08/16/2018, JBHU 317524 was reported leaking upon deramp at BNSF San Bernardino IMF. The waybill lists that the unit was carrying hazardous material. In the interest of safety, the unit was placed on hold and moved to the containment pit pending interior for inspection.  Approved contractor Patriot Environmental was dispatched to remediate the leak at the facility. Interior inspection revealed mixed freight to include shrink wrapped cased goods, 5   gallon shrink wrapped plastic pails, IBC totes and 55   gallon drums. The leaking material was deemed hazardous by Patriot Environmental. The origin of the leak was near the nose of the container; a pallet carrying Zep Mud Slide Concentrate (corrosive liquid, acidic, organic, N.O.S UN3265 ) in 5   gallon plastic pails was found smashed at the bottom of the pallet. Cargo shifted to the side of the pallet causing 3 pails to crack at the bottom. Approximately 12 gallons of product was spilled.
column169: Proper blocking and bracing of mixed loads to ensure materials are not damaged during transport.

On 08/30/2018 at 0120 hours CSXT personnel in the Osborn Yard (Louisville, KY) discovered  GATX 62631, a loaded tank car of Hydrochloric Acid leaking from top of the car. The car was  isolated and the shipper, Arkema was notified. Environmental Management Specialists(EMS),  a CSXT response contractor, responded and found that the rupture disk had ruptured during  switching operations. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the  shipper, Arkema  (Garrick Ramage 270-969-0700). EMS replaced the rupture disk. The tank car  continued in transportation without further delays. This did not require a special switch.     NAR Cause Code: 119 – Frangible Disc – 303 – Burst – 515 – Human Error   Louisville, KY – 08/30/18 –GATX 62631 – Hydrochloric Acid

column168: At 20:30 ET, ERTS received a call from Nick with Emergency Environmental Services, a network contractor with ERTS. Contractors stated they witnessed a Tractor / trailer, license plate number (2489234) roll over on I-10 east bound at MM330 outside of Wilcox, AZ. Contractor stated once the tractor rolled over it impacting the soil on the shoulder of the highway and asphalt. Contractor stated the responsible party regarding this incident is Landstar. Contractor stated the highway is shut down due to the release and everybody (1000 ft in proximity) has been evacuated due to the product releasing and reacting with the soil and diesel fuel. ERTS contacted Landstar and they did indeed take responsible of this incident and requested the contractor to aid in the cleanup of the spill. ERTS notified the state, NRC, local SERC, and AZDOT due to this incident causing shut downs and the regulatory reporting exceeded. Also informing Travis Quails with AZDOT. Contractors confirmed 200 gallons of product released, which is also 10.75-lbs. Contractors cleaned all impacted areas and then secured the site for future remediation.

column168: The driver was going west on US HWY 50 headed to Hillsboro, OH loaded with 4000 gallons of gasoline. While traveling down the road just east of Bainbridge, OH at approximately 1400 the driver traveled off the right side of the highway onto the shoulder which resulted in the unit overturning across the road and bursting into flames. No other parties were involved in the accident. The driver was able to crawl out of the back-tractor cab window. He sustained a burn on his hand from the muffler. Lykins Transportation, Inc. (LTI) was notified of the situation at approximately 1500 by the Ohio EPA. At this point the Paxton Township Fire Department, Ross Co. Emergency Management Agency, Ohio EPA, and Ohio State Patrol were on scene conducting their emergency response. The driver was unable to notify LTI at the time of the incident per LTI incident reporting procedures because all communication devices were in the cab of the truck. Next, LTI made required regulatory reporting, (NRC # 1221311 & OH EPA # 1808EPA1487), and mobilized their environmental response/remediation contractors, Environmental Management Specialists, Inc. (EMS) to assess and conduct spill clean-up efforts. LTI management staff then headed to the scene of the incident, in order, to communicate with local, state, & federal agencies. And, to aid in the clean-up efforts. Around 1800, the HazMat release/fire had stopped. Most of the hazardous material burned in the fire with around 500 gallons impacting the ground adjacent to the roadway. Ohio DOT replaced/repaired the road within the first 48 hours after the incident occurred. And, over the next two weeks all clean-up efforts were completed by EMS per the Ohio EPA’s discretion/standards.
column169: Lykins Transportation, Inc. (LTI) reviews all incidents, in order, to determine the root cause, preventability, and what actions, i.e. training or procedures, need to be conducted or implemented so that the incident will not happen again. The rollover was cause by the driver going off the road. During the next round of safety meetings this fall, LTI will brief all drivers about the incident and review the dangers of and what to do in the event their vehicle runs off or is forced off the road.

column168: On 08/30/2018 at 0715 EST, ERTS received a call from XPO Logistics, Terminal XNJ concerning a spill of 5-gallons of a Hazardous, UN3266, Corrosive liquid. It was reported by XPO, that due to improper loading (too many products shrink wrapped together on a pallet) and the weight of the freight caused the shipment to shift during transit, crushing a (5) -gallon plastic pail and releasing product on to the floor of Trailer#3216360. ERTS was unable to locate an SDS due to not having the trade name but differed to the Hazardous label on the BOL to determine that XPO personnel should not attempt to contain this spill internally.  At 0900 EST, Contractor arrived on site and begin laying speedy dry onto the impacted areas. ERTS  instructed the contractor to remove the damaged pail from the metal drum and we will use only a poly drum for corrosive material. Contractor placed a pH test and it read 14. Contractor applied neutralizer. 5 gallons reported to have released with a nose of trailer being an impacted area of (4' X 5') and a (2' X 3') puddle midway inside the trailer. At 1023 EST, Contractor reports that he used Spilfyter to neutralize the corrosive material.  At 1029 EST, Contractor reports that the trailer was cleaned and neutralized to a pH of 7. Contractor generated (1) 55-gal poly over pack drum for damaged pail and (1) 30-gal poly drum for absorbents used. All waste was left on site for XPO terminal's OS&D to manage. At 1145 EST, Contractor reports to be off-site and all clean up activities complete.

column168: Waycross, GA – 08/25/2018 – WACX 151168 – Phosphoric Acid Solution  On 8/25/18, at 1954, personnel in the CSXT Rice Yard discovered WACX 151168, a loaded tank car of  Phosphoric acid solution, leaking from the bottom center of the tank car. The car was isolated and  PCS Sales (USA) INC, Waycross Fire Department, Georgia EPD, and NRC (report #1222715) were  notified.  CHEMTREC report #2018-0825-00121. Hulls Environmental, a CSXT emergency response  contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found WACX 151168 leaking from the bottom center of  the tank car. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper  Paul Duckworth, 706-564-8423. Contractor personnel contained the release and transferred the  remaining product to UTLX 300054.  WACX 151168 was cleaned and purged and the release area  was remediated.  Inspection of WACX 151168 revealed three pinholes at the bottom of the inner  tank near the weld seam, thus indicating corrosion of the interior lining of the tank car.   A deteriorated gasket was found when the bottom outlet flange was removed for inspection.   This incident did require a 7.1.

The car was isolated and Kapstone Paper and Packaging Corporation, Waycross Fire Department,  Georgia Environmental protecton division (report #87340), and NRC (report #1223357) were notified. CYLINDER CAME SEPARATELY FROM OUTER PACKAGING TO THE DMP/CLERKS AREA BECAUSE WE ALSO DEAL WITH DAMAGES, FALLOUTS, OVERGOODS, ETC. THE CYLINDER IS FROM AMTROL SO I LOOKED AT THEIR WEBSITE TO DETERMINE IF THE CYLINDER SHOULD BE EMPTY AND WHAT IT WAS MEANT FOR. THE INFORMATION ABOUT IT INDICATES IT'S A 50LB REFILLABLE CYLINDER FOR THE RECOVERY OF REFRIGERANT GAS. ITS TARE WEIGHT IS 27.6LB, BUT WHEN I WEIGHED IT, IT'S 29.30LB; IT ALSO HISSES WHEN THE VALVES ARE OPENED. THERE ARE NO INDICATIONS ON THE CYLINDER OR THE BOX THAT THE CYLINDER IS EMPTY. THESE FACTORS LED ME TO THINK IT IS POSSIBLY AN UNDECLARED HAZMAT. THERE ARE NO HAZ MARKINGS ON THE EXTERNAL BOX THAT CAME OPEN ALONG WITH THE CYLINDER AND IT APPEARS REUSED. JENNIFER AT HMSC SAID TO HOLD PACKAGE FOR ADG INSPECTION, EMAIL 6-SIDED PHOTOS TO THE COMPLIANCE DEPARTMENT, AND COMPLETE THE ETT DOCUMENTATION. REFERENCE #954507.
column169: MAKE SURE CUSTOMERS UNDERSTAND THEIR RESPONSIBILITY IN SHIPPING DANGEROUS GOODS.

column168: Drum of waste was dropped off at a house hold waste event. Drum was inspected and prepared for shipment. Drum was loaded and properly secured for transport to our truck to truck facility. Spill clean up material was placed into salvage container along with damaged drum and shipped off to final disposal destination. No state notification was required due to not meeting sate reporting requirments.
column169: Moving forward, any drums that are brought to a household hazardous waste pick up event, will be given a proper and thorough inspection. Any drums found not in shippable condition, will be repackaged into a new drum. Old drum will be properly disposed of properly.

column168: During offloading of a transport truck, a release was discovered under a package. A response team was dispatched. In proper personal protective equipment, verified through health and safety, the team was successful in repackaging the material into approved UN specification containers and in remediation of the transport trailer flooring. Washington State Department of Ecology was notified and report #683285 was generated. The package was sent to its final destination without further incident.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking or damage was observed. In order to prevent a recurrence, the personnel who packaged the material have been re-instructed in regards to proper packaging and comprehensive container inspection,  along with the closure device to identify any potential issues before transportation. The local management have also elected to move to using a better suited container for this generator.

column168: Driver Loaded at oil tanking in Channahon, IL on 8/29/18. Oil tanking inspects the trailer before they load and perform the entire loading process, and close and secure the dome after loading, as drivers are not allowed to climb ladders on the shippers property.  The dome lid gasket fell out unnoticed as the loaders closed and secured the dome after loading. The driver was making a stop and a Gibson, IL police car was behind him and notice what appeared to  liquid coming from the top of the trailer. It had been raining and the driver was unaware of any leak. Once the leak was confirmed, the police and fire department closed the road, and the shipper was called to get permission to cut the seal off the dome lid to inspect, and that's when the gasket was found missing. A new gasket was installed and he driver performed a slosh test with no leaks, and was allowed to proceed to the customer for delivery.
column169: Shippers need to verify the dome gaskets are in place before they tighten and seal the dome lid since the drivers are not allowed to check them.

Package was discovered on atruck by QA working VSA, WA677. Leaked about .3 GAL. Package was not in upright position when discovered. This Hazmat should not have passed the HAP process. IT was lacking proper packaging. Packing group II requires "X" or "Y" UN POP packaging. UN POP packaging was not used. Flammable liquids, corrosive, n.o.s. requires DOT Flammable liquid and corrosive diamond labels. Only Flammable liquid DOT diamond label was on the packaging, no corrosive label. If UN POP packaging was used, damage could have been avoided.  New Comments:

column168: On 08/25/2018 at 0257 hours, CSXT personnel in Maxwell Yard (Greenwood, SC) reported UTLX 200751, a loaded car of Hydrogen Peroxide leaking from the top of the car after the car was derailed and turned over on its side. The tank car was isolated and and the shipper Solvay Chemicals Inc was notified. HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor responded and found product leaking from around the liquid line of the tank car. HEPACO attempted to stop the leak but was unable to stop the leak. Containment was placed under the liquid line until the tank car was turned upright. Solvay Duke Spencer Ph#360-967-2334 was contacted and advised of all actions taken. A hold has been placed on the tank car and it will be transferred into another tank car. This did require a special move.    Nar Cause Code:  133 Liquid Line  308 Leaked  509 Derailment    NRC Report number 1222641

column168: At 1605 ET, ERTS was contacted by Bri Timmons of Covenant Transportation Group about a cargo release. It was reported that due to improper loading approximately 1 gallon of hazardous UN1824 Sodium Hydroxide Solution released from (1) 275 gallon poly tote. The released product was contained to the trailer floor, the trucks tires, and the parking lot asphalt. There were no drains, soils or waterways reported to have been impacted by the release. ERTS dispatched Advanced Environmental Solutions to perform cleanup. At  2037 ET, the contractor arrived onsite and confirmed 1.5 gallons of product were released to the trailer. The leak was due to a valve left open. Due to the tote being older, the contractor could not confirm that the valve would stay secure for further transit. The contractor transferred the product into a new tote and cleaned all impacted areas. All waste was placed into (1) 55 gallon metal drum and the drum and damaged tote were taken off site for proper disposal. No further cleanup is necessary.

column168: 1. On 08/02/18, a shipment containing hazmat identified as UN3166 was received by Hawaiian Airlines (HA) cargo agent in Osaka, Japan.  for transport through HNL to LAS. The article was packaged under the airway bill (AWB) 173-3599-7780 2. The shipment traveled on 08/02/18 HA449  from KIX-HNL. The required paperwork including the shipper’s declaration and Notice to Pilot In Command (NOPIC) accompanied the shipment from KIX-HNL. 3. The shipment was held overnight in HNL awaiting clearance from customs to be transported on the second flight segment from HNL-LAS. While awaiting clearance from customs in HNL, the Chief Cargo Agent on Duty separated the AWB and NOPIC from the 1st flight segment from the build up card. 4. Once the shipment cleared customs on 08/03/18, it was prepared for transport from HNL-LAS on HA 18. 5. On 8/4/18, the Chief Cargo Agent on Duty in HNL became aware that the required NOPIC for the  shipment sent on 8/3/18 did not accompany the shipment. The shipment containing dangerous goods traveled without the required NOPIC. 6. There was no failure of the package.  The root cause of the incident was that the Company's policy on the acceptance and handling of  dangerous goods were not properly followed.   According to 49 CFR 175.33 - Shipping paper and notification of pilot-in-command: The NOPIC document must be presented to the PIC for signature and carried onboard the  aircraft for the duration of the flight.  The HA Cargo Manual Section 7.7.4 states that a NOPIC must be completed and presented to the load master. The load master will then present the NOPIC to the PIC once the hazmat has been loaded. The HA Cargo Manual Section 7.7.4.A.1 states that if the shipment is scheduled to make an online transfer, two (2)  separate NOPIC forms are to be prepared.  The action of separating the NOPIC from the article caused the shipment to be carried on the aircraft without the proper notification to the PIC
column169: HA Cargo Chief was counseled and advised of having the required shipping documents remain with the shipment at all times.  HA Cargo operations are reviewing documentation procedures and developing revised Standard Operating Procedures (SOPs) to ensure that future omission of required shipping documents does not occur.

column168: The Lykins Transportation, Inc. (LTI) driver had arrived at the destination, Estes Express in Columbus, Ohio. The delivery was for a full load, 7500 gallons, of on-road diesel fuel. The facility has two underground storage tanks (UST), labeled north tank and south tank, and they are filled from a remote fill-port about 20 feet away from the UST fill-pipe caps. The fill-pipe caps are normally locked out and the only way to gauge the tanks is by getting a Veeder-root reading from the facility. Both tanks showed they could hold more than 5000 gallons of product before becoming 90% full. Therefore, there was more than enough room for the delivery. The LTI driver hooked up to the remote fill-port and started unloading the product at approximately 1150. After a few of minutes went by the LTI driver noticed something was not right and saw product flowing out the top of the UST south tank cap. The product was rushing out the top of the UST and was running down into the facility’s detention basin adjacent to the USTs. The LTI driver acted by stopping the flow of product and quickly grabbed a bunch of spills pads to mitigate the spill. At approximately 1200 LTI Dispatch was informed of the incident. LTI Dispatch than informed LTI Environmental Director who happened to be in Columbus area and responded to the scene directly to assess the situation. At 1235 the LTI Environmental Director was on-scene with the LTI driver and Estes Express personnel. At 1255 LTI spill response contractors, Environmental Management Specialists, Inc (EMS) were notified of the spill. Next, LTI than made all required regulatory reporting notifications: NRC # 1221638, Ohio EPA # 1808EPA1511, and Franklin County EMA. EMS was on-site at 1325 to assess and began clean-up efforts. EMS worked through the evening until the next morning until the spill clean-up efforts and environmental remediation was completed. LTI determined that both themselves and Estes Express were responsible for the spill. The spill was caused by something malfunctioning within the UST’s and remote fill-port system and overfill prevention devices. The UST fill-pipe cap was not locked out, and something within the remote fill did not work correctly, and the south tank’s flapper value did not work which could have prevented the overfill. Also, the spill was a result of the time it took for the driver to shut-off the flow of product which aided in the spill. The spill was contained within the facility’s detention basin and did not leave Estes Express property.
column169: Lykins Transportation, Inc. (LTI) reviews all incidents, in order, to determine the root cause, preventability, and what actions, i.e. training or procedures, need to be conducted or implemented so that the incident will not happen again. The spill was caused by both the customer’s UST system and the time it took for the driver to notice the spill occurring. LTI conducts driver safety meetings three times a year. During the next round of them in the fall, LTI will brief all drivers about the incident and review with them the importance of being alert at the point of discharge. Having great attentional awareness at the point of discharge truly makes the different when events like happen. Also, for Part III, question 25 the best packing failure code associated with this incident was chosen. Something went wrong internally with the UST system’s remote fill piping and the overfill prevention device. Therefore, human error was chosen because both parties were at fault. The UST system was not properly maintained, and the driver could have noticed the spill occurring much earlier.

During routine offloading of a transport trailer, a series of containers were identified as compromised with portions of their contents released and seeping from the UN rated containers. The released was contained to the transport trailer, no land, soil, water ways or storm drains were impacted by this release. A report of this release was called into Ed Costomeris of the Utah Department of Environmental Quality. No state report number was generated as the released amount did not meet reportable quantity thresholds.

column168: While loading a transport trailer, the driver punctured a drum with the drum dolly he was using to load. The driver immediately minimized the amount released from the compromised drum by tilting it. The other driver contained the release by placing absorbent material on the release. The impact of the release was to the trailer floor only, no land, soil, water ways or storm drains were affected by this release. The team was in appropriate personal protective equipment, verified by the internal health and safety department, as they safely placed the compromised drum into a UN rated salvage drum and remediated the trailer floor. A courtesy report was called into Anne Nedrow of the Colorado Department of Public Health and Environment, who elected not to draft a report number, as the released quantity was below reportable thresholds.
column169: The driver was retrained on drum dolly technique and operations. The driver was also asked to resign a Safety Commitment letter as he was disciplined per policy for a preventable release.

column168: 1.Hawaiian Airlines (HA) accepted a shipment which included five (5) pieces identified by the Air Way Bill (AWB) 173-31248674  and tendered for transport on HA11 16AUG2018 SFO-HNL. The shipment contained dangerous goods (DG) and the proper paper work was completed for the shipment including the shipper's declaration and Notification to the Pilot in Command (NOPIC). 2. The shipment transited through HNL prior to its final destination in LIH.   3. Three (3) pieces containing DG traveled on HA503 HNL-LIH. The required NOPIC for the shipment traveling to LIH was prepared and placed on the HazMat clipboard.  The Cargo runner was notified that the NOPICs were on the clipboard and instructed to retrieve the NOPICs when each shipment was moved to the aircraft. 6. The cargo runner in HNL failed to retrieve the NOPIC from the Hazmat clipboard prior to delivering the shipments to the aircraft.  The root cause of the incident was that the Company's policy on the acceptance and handling of dangerous goods was not properly followed. According to 49 CFR 175.33 - Shipping paper and notification of pilot-in-command: The NOPIC document must be presented to the pilot in command (PIC) for signature and carried onboard the aircraft for the duration of the flight.  Furthermore the HA Cargo Manual Section 7.7.4 states that a NOPIC must be completed and  presented to the load master and PIC. The load master will then present the NOPIC to the PIC once the hazmat has been loaded. The HA Cargo Manual Section 7.7.4.A.1 states that if the shipment is scheduled to make an online transfer, two (2) separate NOPIC forms are to be prepared. The action of separating the NOPIC from the shipment caused the shipment to carried on the aircraft with out the proper notification to the PIC.  There was no failure of the package
column169: The cargo runner and chief on duty were counseled regarding the requirements of the NOPIC being transmitted with the shipments to the aircraft.  Due to the repeated events involving the omission of the required documentation (NOPIC) involving incidents in the HA cargo operations, revised standard operating procedures (SOPs) are being developed to improve the handling and transmittal of hazmat documentation. The SOPs presently being reviewed are to include the following; 1. Upon acceptance of the shipment containing hazmat, the shipment will be placed in a hazmat/dangerous  goods staging area. 2.   All required documents for the shipment placed in the staging area will be provided to the Chief on Duty. 3. Chief agent will verify documentation and approves release of the shipment prior to removal from the  the staging area.  An approval notation (green label with employee initials and number) will be applied to the AWB indicating that the documents have been verified. 4. All approved documents will accompany the shipment to the aircraft.

THE PASSENGER VEHICLE INVOLVED IN THE TRAFFIC STOP WAS ALSO STRUCK BY THE CMV RESULTING IN DAMAGE TO THE DRIVER’S SIDE FRONT AND REAR PANEL.  THE CMV THEN STRUCK A GUARD RAIL WHICH CAUSED THE CMV TO ROLL-OVER AND LEAVE THE ROADWAY. THE ACCIDENT RESULTED IN THE CMV DRIVER’S FATALITY AND A SPILL OF ABOUT 5,000 GALLONS OF GASOLINE WHICH WAS CONTAINED ON LAND AROUND THE ACCIDENT. THE INVESTIGATION IS ONGOING, AND FLEET TRANSIT, INC. IS WORKING CLOSELY WITH THE INVESTIGATING OFFICER – SGT. ERIC GREGSON OF THE MARYLAND STATE POLICE CRASH TEAM (PHONE: 410-996-7838, EMAIL: ERIC.GREGSON@MARYLAND.GOV). SPILL REMEDIATION IS BEING CONDUCTED BY ACE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES.

column168: A VEHICLE HAD BECOME DISABLED AND WAS PARTIALLY BLOCKING THE RIGHT LANE OF I-495 NORTHBOUND, APPROXIMATELY .25 MILES SOUTH OF THE PHILADELPHIA PIKE OFF-RAMP. A SECOND VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING NORTHBOUND I-495 IN THE RIGHT LANE WHEN SHE OBSERVED THE DISABLED VEHICLE AND SWERVED LEFT TO AVOID A COLLISION, BUT COULD NOT DO SO, AND IN TURN, THE RIGHT SIDE OF HER VEHICLE STRUCK THE LEFT SIDE OF THE DISABLED VEHICLE.  AFTER THE INITIAL COLLISION THE ORIGINALLY DISABLED VEHICLE REMAINED DISABLED IN THE RIGHT LANE.  AT THIS TIME, A 2018 VOLVO TANK, TRAVELING I-495 NORTHBOUND IN THE RIGHT LANE, WAS ALSO UNABLE TO SEE THE DISABLED VEHICLE, AND IN TURN, THE FRONT END OF HIS VEHICLE STRUCK THE REAR END OF THE DISABLED VEHICLE. AS A RESULT OF THE COLLISION, THE VOLVO OVERTURNED ON TO IT’S LEFT SIDE AND BEGAN SLIDING IN THE NORTHEASTERLY DIRECTION, WITH THE CAB PORTION OF THE VOLVO STRIKING A GUARDRAIL BEFORE COMING TO REST.  THE OPERATOR OF THE VOLVO TANKER TRUCK, WHO WAS PROPERLY RESTRAINED, WAS PRONOUNCED DECEASED AT THE SCENE. THERE WAS NO LEAKAGE OF THE MOLTEN SULFUR, WHICH WAS CONTAINED IN THE TANKER, HOWEVER, THE ROADWAY WAS CLOSED FOR APPROXIMATELY 11 HOURS WHILE THE SCENE WAS INVESTIGATED AND CLEARED.
column169: NOTHING AT THIS TIME. TRAILER SAFETY DEVICES PERFORMED AS INTENDED TO PREVENT MATERIAL LEAKAGE. UNFORTUNATELY, OUR DRIVER CAME UP ON A DARK COLORED VEHICLE ON A DARK STRETCH OF INTERSTATE IN HIS LANE, WITH NO HAZARDS OR FLASHING LIGHTS AND WAS UNABLE TO AVOID THE VEHICLE.

column168: During routine offloading of a transport trailer, a container was identified as compromised with portions of its contents released and seeping from the UN rated container. A response team was dispatched. In appropriate personal protective equipment, the response team was successful in repackaging the material into new UN specification rated containers and in remediation of the transport trailer floor. The released was contained to the transport trailer, no land, soil, water ways or storm drains were impacted by this release. A report of this release was called into Ed Costomeris of the Utah Department of Environmental Quality. No state report number was generated as the released amount did not meet reportable quantity thresholds.
column169: The generator and broker were notified of the compromised container and subsequent release. The shipper was advised on proper package selection to ensure that waste streams were packaged properly into approved UN specification rated containers to prevent future releases.

column168: Original comments:  PACKAGE PICKED UP BY DRIVER TODAY NOTICED AN ODOR COMING FROM PACKAGE AND MADE SHIPPER AWARE OF THE BUT WAS ASSURED IT WAS FINE. PACKAGE ARRIVED AT STATION WITH WET OUTER PACKAGING WET.INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE 1 GAL DRUM OF THINNER WAS PUNCTURED. ALSO WHEN LOOKING UP THE SDS FOR THIS PRODUCT, THE INFORMATION THAT  WAS PUT ON THE OP-900 AND OP-950 DID NOT MATCH WHAT WAS IN THE SDS.  New Comments:

The product being unloaded was from a Vendor arranged shipment and it was not Harcros Chemicals Inc. owned equipment.  On Monday, 08/13/2018 at 16:30, while unloading a tanker of Techmide 180(Amide C), a warehouse operator noticed that flow completely stopped while filling drum 60 of 60(at 440 lbs of a 480 Ib drum). The operator looked out the window and noticed that the unloading hose was completely disconnected from the tanker, as the locking camlock fitting had one lock that was wom and wouldn't completely close. The operator immediately went outside and closed the internal valve on the tank. The operator reconnected the hose and went back inside to finish unloading the truck. The last drum was completely filled and a tote was placed on the drumming station and filled to 1,440 lbs. However, 2,585 lbs of material had poured from the tanker and into containment. From there, the material flows to the wastewater treatment pond. On 08/14/2018 at 14:20, a call was made to Mark Buckner at Dalton Utilities where Harcros Chemicals Inc. informed him of the spill and that we would discharge our pond water to them and stay within our permitted limits on,pH, COD, and TSS.
column169: The operator was trained on what to look for when getting a locking Camlock fitting to lock on both sides. j

column168: When employee went to unload the contents of the truck, he opened the first valve before taking the cap off the offload valve. Debris had been jammed in the second valve and allowed some of the liquid to leak out. When he removed the cap, 18.22KG's (2 gallons) released on to the ground. The release occurred on asphalt, and no drains were compromised. Employee had on proper PPE and cleaned up the spill. All spill debris was placed in a drum, and properly disposed of. Shipper contacted the State of NY to report the release.
column169: Driver was retrained on the proper procedure to offload liquids. Driver was instructed not to open any valve before removing cap. Also driver was instructed to check valves to ensure there is no debris preventing the valve from closing.

column168: CARGOLOUX GROUND HANDLER (GHA) "SWISSPORT" EMPLOYEE WAS UNDERSTAFFED. EMPLOYEE DECIDED TO LOAD THE PMC BY HIMSELF. HE DROVE A FORKLIFT UP TO THE PMC AND PUSHED IT ON TO THE LOADER WITH THE FORKS. THE RUPTURED A 15.5 LITER DRUM. THE CONTENTS SPILLED ON TO THE AIRCRAFT PALLET. THE EMPLOYEE THEN LOADED THE PALLET ON THE AIRCRAFT AND SHUT THE DOOR. THE CREW ON THE FLIGHT DECK SMELLED THE ODOR AND WENT TO INVESTIGATE. THEY COULD FIND NOTHING ON THE MAIN DECK AND THEN HAD THE LOWER FORWARD HOLD OF THE AIRCRAFT OPENED. ONCE OPENED IT WAS OBVIOUS WHERE THE SMELL WAS ORIGINATING. PALLET WAS REMOVED FROM THE AIRCRAFT. AN UNDETERMINED AMOUNT OP PRODUCT LEAKED INTO THE AIRCRAFT WHILE THE PMC WAS BEING MOVED ON AND OFF THE AIRCRAFT. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED TO CHECK IT OUT BUT DID NOT SEEMED CONCERNED. WE CONTACTED A CLEAN UP CREW / HAZMAT TEAM TO CLEAN UP. THE CREW CAME OUT CLEANED UP THE AIRCRAFT / PMC / ANY SUBSEQUENT WOOD THAT CAME IN CONTACT WITH THE PRODUCT. PLACED ALL OF THE SUBSTANCE INTO 4 STEEL DRUMS AND SEALED THEM.
column169: THE GHA "SWISSPORT" IMMEDIATELY TERMINATED THE EMPLOYEE FOLLOWING THE INVESTIGATION. SWISSPORT EMPLOYEES KNOW VERY WELL NOT TO USE A FORKLIFTS TO MOVE FREIGHT NEAR THE AIRCRAFT. THE GHA HAS BRIEFED ALL EMPLOYEES ON CARGOLUX POLICIES INVOLVING THE HANDLING OF DANGEROUS GOOD AND SAFETY.

column168: At approximately 12:30pm, while driving a Minibulk trailer (five 650-gallon tanks mounted on flatbed trailer) in Alameda County, California, en route to San Jose, California, the driver observed in his side mirror liquid coming from the tank on his trailer.  He immediately pulled over to a dirt area off to the side of the on-ramp to the freeway to assess the situation and how best to contain the spill.  Upon inspection, the driver realized that emergency assistance was necessary.  He immediately called 911 to request emergency assistance and then called his Branch Manager to apprise him of the situation.  The Hayward Fire Department and its hazmat response team arrived on scene and contained approximately 300 gallons of KMS-10 (Nitric/Phosphoric Acid blend) that had leaked from tank #3 on the trailer. Details of this response action are provided in the Hayward Fire Department reports identified in item 31 above.  Environmental contractor Clean Harbors was dispatched to remediate the scene. Upon further investigation it was discovered that the pipe had failed at the weld on the outlet pipe on the bottom of the tank.
column169: Inspect all fleet portable tank installations for weld integrity.   Develop a company-wide Safety Alert for MiniBulk Trailers, disseminate to all operations employees, and discuss in detail during Safety Stand-Down.

column168: Driver was on a delivery run moving motor fuel from loading point in Austin, Texas to delivery point in Lampasas, Texas.  While northbound on US183, a paved, single lane roadway each direction, driver was travelling approximately 60 mph in a 70 mph zone.  Driver allowed right front steer tire to roll off the pavement edge onto the grassy shoulder.  Driver over corrected steering action to the left.  Vehicle came back entirely onto the roadway, jack knifed, and overturned onto right side of the semi-trailer.  The vehicle slid on its side to a stop across the north bound lane.  The sliding motion of the semi-trailer caused abrasions to the shell which allowed product leakage.  First responders arrived to secure the scene and temporarily close the roadway to deny public access.   Local environmental response team, Groens Environmental of Waco, Texas responded to the scene.  Soil removal and remediation efforts have been performed by Groens Environmental.  TCEQ has provided onsite guidance to the environmental response team during the remediation work.
column169: Onboard video review indicates that the driver was not using an electronic device or asleep at the wheel.  Driver was not paying full attention to the driving task and allowed the cargo tank motor vehicle to wander to the right side of the roadway and leave the pavement edge. column168: Driver was on a delivery run moving motor fuel from loading point in Austin, Texas to delivery point in Lampasas, Texas.  While northbound on US183, a paved, single lane roadway each direction, driver was travelling approximately 60 mph in a 70 mph zone.  Driver allowed right front steer tire to roll off the pavement edge onto the grassy shoulder.  Driver over corrected steering action to the left.  Vehicle came back entirely onto the roadway, jack knifed, and overturned onto right side of the semi-trailer.  The vehicle slid on its side to a stop across the north bound lane.  The sliding motion of the semi-trailer caused abrasions to the shell which allowed product leakage.  First responders arrived to secure the scene and temporarily close the roadway to deny public access.   Local environmental response team, Groens Environmental of Waco, Texas responded to the scene.  Soil removal and remediation efforts have been performed by Groens Environmental.  TCEQ has provided onsite guidance to the environmental response team during the remediation work.

column168: Driver and the Village of Pewaukee employee were at Well #6.  Driver delivered 660 lbs of 12.5% sodium hypochlorite solution into a phosphate tank. Both the Village employee and the driver left the property without detecting any release of chlorine. At approx. 11:30 am a Village employee returned to well #6 and encountered chemical vapors.  Employee was evacuated and sent to hospital as standard treatment for chemical vapor exposure.  After a period of observation the employee was release at approx. 5pm after it was determined that he had suffered no injury.  Waukesha FD hazmat team was onsite and entered the well house approx. 5:30pm and detected low amounts of chlorine.  Based upon delivery volumes and an analysis of the contents of the phosphate tank it was determined that  76lbs of chlorine were released from the sodium hypochlorite.
column169: We are reinforcing the need to read labels and confirm the correct tank is being pumped into.  The tanks themselves were clearly marked and this was a failure of the employee to follow established procedure and positively identify the tank before delivery.

column168: Veolia personnel were loading the tanker using a diaphragm pump.  When loading was completed,  the pump continued pumping residual material from the hose into the tanker to terminate the filling  operation.  Once all the material from the hose was cleared, an air bubble got pushed into the tanker  which caused the dome lid to lift up slightly and splash the liquid on the ground.
column169: The loading connection is located at the bottom of the tank, right below the top hatch.  The air bubble was able to lift the top hatch slightly, releasing the splash of material.  To prevent a future spill,  additional precautions have been taken such as reduce the fill level for CTMVs and assign an additional  observer to monitor for safe loading.

column168: 1.Hawaiian Airlines (HA) accepted a shipment which included five (5) pieces identified by the Air Way Bill (AWB) 173-31248674  and tendered for transport on HA11 16AUG2018 SFO-HNL. The shipment contained dangerous goods (DG) and the proper paper work was completed for the shipment including the shipper's declaration and Notification to the Pilot in Command (NOPIC). 2. The shipment transited through HNL prior to its final destination in LIH.   3. When the shipment was received in HNL, it was split into two (2) separate shipments for movement on separate flights. 4. Two (2) pieces traveled on HA363 HNL-LIH on  16AUG18. 5. The required NOPICs for each shipment traveling to LIH were prepared and placed on the HazMat clipboard. The Cargo runner was  notified that the NOPICs were on the clipboard and instructed to retrieve the NOPICs when each shipment was moved to the aircraft. 6. The cargo runner in HNL failed to retrieve the NOPICs from the Hazmat clipboard prior to delivering the shipments to the aircraft.  The root cause of the incident was that the Company's policy on the acceptance and handling of dangerous goods was not properly followed. According to 49 CFR 175.33 - Shipping paper and notification of pilot-in-command: The NOPIC document must be presented to the pilot in command (PIC) for signature and carried onboard the aircraft for the duration of the flight.  Furthermore the HA Cargo Manual Section 7.7.4 states that a NOPIC must be completed and  presented to the load master and PIC. The load master will then present the NOPIC to the PIC once the hazmat has been loaded. The HA Cargo Manual Section 7.7.4.A.1 states that if the shipment is scheduled to make an online transfer, two (2) separate NOPIC forms are to be prepared. The action of separating the NOPIC from the shipment caused the shipment to carried on the aircraft with out the proper notification to the PIC.  There was no failure of the package
column169: The cargo runner and chief on duty were counseled regarding the requirements of the NOPIC being transmitted with the shipments to the aircraft. Due to the repeated events involving the omission of the required documentation (NOPIC) involving incidents in the HA cargo operations, revised standard operating procedures (SOPs) are being developed to improve the handling and transmittal of hazmat documentation. The SOPs presently being reviewed are to include the following; 1. Upon acceptance of the shipment containing hazmat, the shipment will be placed in a hazmat/dangerous goods staging area. 2. All required documents for the shipment placed in the staging area will be provided to the Chief on Duty. 3. Chief agent will verify documentation and approves release of the shipment prior to removal from the the staging area. An approval notation (green label with employee initials and number) will be applied to the AWB indicating that the documents have been verified. 4. All approved documents will accompany the shipment to the aircraft

column168: Driver was filling a 5250 gallon ASME bulk storage tank at a customers facility.  While filling the container the pressure relief valve on the receiving tank failed resulting in a release of product to the atmosphere.  The tank was at approximately 72% capacity when the relief valve failed.  The relief valve reset when the tank capacity was approximately 55% resulting in a release of an estimated 900 gallons of propane to the atmosphere.  The tank was isolated and plugged on the site.  Prior to removal all remaining liquid was pumped from the storage tank and depressurized.  The tank was subsequently removed from the customer location for repair.
column169: Tank was removed and replaced with 2 1000 gallon ASME tanks.  Relief device was removed, but no testing was performed on the component to determine a reason fro failure.

column168: 1.Hawaiian Airlines (HA) accepted a cargo shipment which included three (3) pieces identified by the Air Way Bill (AWB) 131-72073186 and tendered for transport on HA821 29AUG2018 HNL-NRT. The shipment contained dangerous goods (DG) and the proper paper work was completed for the shipment including the shipper's declaration and Notification to the Pilot in Command (NOPIC). 2. The cargo shipment was delivered to the aircraft with the NOPIC. 3. The load master (LM) loaded the cargo shipment on the aircraft. 4. At 1531 the flight departed and the LM realized that he had overlooked providing the Pilot in Command (PIC). 5. The Load Planner Chief contacted HA dispatch and an ACARS was sent to the flight to advise of the NOPIC not provided to the PIC and that the DG was loaded in compartment 1.  The specifics of the shipment were provided to the PIC including, position in aircraft, and that the shipment contained UN1845 Dry Ice with a total weight of 42 lbs. (20.4 kg). 6. A confirmation was received by the PIC via ACARS noting the acknowledgement of the DG in the forward compartment and was  received by dispatch via a message from the System Operations Control Center (SOCC) 7. The PIC also received the final load closeout sheet prior to the departure of the aircraft that  indicated the dry ice was loaded in the forward compartment of the aircraft. 8. There was no failure of the package  The root cause of the incident was that the Company's policy on the acceptance and handling of dangerous goods was not properly followed. According to 49 CFR 175.33 - Shipping paper and notification of pilot-in-command: The NOPIC document must be presented to the pilot in command (PIC) for signature and carried onboard the aircraft for the duration of the flight.  The HA Passenger Service Manual (PSM) Section 10.3.1.D. states that after the DG is loaded to the  aircraft the LM must complete the location section of the NOPIC, sign it, obtain the PIC's  signature and leave the original with the PIC.  The Ground Service Manual (GSM) Section G, Chapter 4, Item 3.0 states provides the procedures  for the completion of the NOPIC any time DG is transported on HA flight.  The LM failed to properly follow the HA's procedures which caused the shipment to be  carried on the aircraft without the required NOPIC.
column169: The LM was counseled by the manager on duty on 30AUG2018 regarding the requirements of the NOPIC being presented to the PIC prior to the departure  of the aircraft. A record of corrective action (ROCA) was placed in the LM personnel file.  The LM had received proper Hazmat awareness training and was current on the training. In order to emphasize the policies and procedures for DG loading on the aircraft, Airport Operations posted the polices to the electronic monitoring boards in the operational area stating,  " No aircraft with Dangerous Goods (DG) SHALL be cleared WITHOUT a NOPIC delivered to  the Pilot in Command (PIC)."

column169: EVEN THOUGH THIS PARTICULAR ACCIDENT WAS NON-PREVENTABLE, TANK ROLLOVER TRAINING IS ADVISED. THE TRAINING CAN INCLUDE HOW TO PREVENT ROLLOVER, WHAT FACTORS CAN CAUSE A ROLLOVER, AND WHAT TO DO AFTER A ROLLOVER OCCURS (EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN).   IT IS ALSO RECOMMENDED THAT A SIGNAL BE PUT AT THE INTERSECTION THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED. THIS WILL HELP WITH SPEED ON THE HIGHWAY AND HELP IMPROVE THE OVERALL SAFETY OF ALL DRIVERS AT THIS BUSY INTERSECTION.

column168: On August 29, 2018 GATX 203150 was reported leaking in the BNSF Wellington, KS Yard. Upon observation, there was frost on the protective housing and down the side of the tank car. The local BNSF Hazmat responder was able to assess the car and close the open liquid valve and stop the leak. Hazmat Contractor HMRI and SRS were also dispatched to the location to further assess the valves and closures. It was determined that the secondary closure for the liquid valve (drylock fitting) had a bad o-ring which allowed a leak from the secondary closure. The drylock fittings were replaced prior to OTMA for movement.
column169: Review the loading/unloading inspection procedures to assure that secondary closures are functional and there are no damaged rubber o-rings sticking out of the secondary closure. Inspect/Replace the secondary closures according to manufacturer recommendations.(NAR:313,Drylock fitting o-ring failed)

column168: DRIVER ARRIVED AT SITE WITH 7406 GALS OF DYED DIESEL. DELTA EMPLOYEE SHOWED HIM WHICH TANK TO UNLOAD INTO AND CONFIRMED THAT IT WOULD HOLD. HE STATED THE TANK HAD BEEN STUCK AND THE VALVE BETWEEN THE 2 TANKS HAD BEEN OPENED TO ALLOW EVEN MORE ROOM. AS THE TANKER STOPPED PUMPING FUEL FROM THE LAST COMPARTMENT, AIR WAS FORCING FOAM OUT OF DELTA'S TOP VENT. THE DRIVER STOPPED THE PUMP AND VERIFIED THAT THE TANKER COMPARTMENTS WERE EMPTY. THE CONTAINMENT AREA HAD SEVERAL INCHES OF WATER IN IT BEFORE FROM RAIN AND THE DIESEL RAN DOWN THE TANK WALLS ON TOP OF THE WATER. AT THAT TIME, NO WATER OR DIESEL WAS LEAVING THE CONTAINMENT WALLS. (SEE PHOTO) STAR CALLED E3 ENVIRONMENTAL TO COME REMOVE THE CONTAINED GALLONS OF WATER AND DIESEL. WHEN THEY ARRIVED IT HAD BEEN RAINING AGAIN AND THE CONTAINMENT AREA WAS EMPTY OF ALL LIQUID. (SEE PHOTO) THEY SAW THAT THE CONTAINMENT VALVES WERE OPEN AND THE CONTENTS HAD FLOWED TO THE PUDDLES SURROUNDING THE TANK AREA. E3 CLOSED THE VALVES AND USED A VAC TRUCK TO REMOVE ALL WATER AND FLOATING DIESEL. BOOMS AND PADS WERE USED TO RECLAIM THE REST. NO CONTACT WITH SOIL WAS NOTED BECAUSE OF RAIN WATER.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 9:30 AM, AUGUST 2, 2018, I WAS IN THE OFFICE AT INDUSTRIAL OIL IN KLAMATH FALLS. ROUTE DRIVER ED WARNER CAME RUNNING INTO THE OFFICE TO TELL ME THAT THERE WAS SOMETHING “REALLY BAD” HAPPENING WITH THE ROUTE TRUCK (#0675) ON THE LOADING PAD. I IMMEDIATELY WENT OUTSIDE AND NOTICED A YELLOW-BROWN SMOKE OR VAPOR COMING FROM THE FRONT TOP HATCH OF THE CARGO TANK (SEE VIDEO). AFTER A QUICK ASSESSMENT OF THE SERIOUSNESS OF THE SITUATION, I DECIDED TO CALL 911.  AT THIS POINT THERE WAS A GOOD DEAL OF COMMOTION GOING ON. PRESENT IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA WERE PLANT WORKERS JOE ALLEN AND ERIK COLLMAN, DRIVERS ED WARNER AND DON RANDALL, AND MYSELF. PLANT MANAGER DAVID ARCHULETA WAS AWAY ON A PARTS RUN. WHILE TALKING WITH THE 911 OPERATOR I SAW ERIK COLLMAN RUNNING FROM THE FAR SIDE OF THE TRUCK TOWARDS THE EYE WASH STATION. I THEN FOUND OUT THAT AFTER STOPPING THE PUMP AND CLOSING THE VALVES, HE WAS TRYING TO UNHOOK THE OFFLOADING HOSE. APPARENTLY THERE HAD BEEN SOME PRESSURE BUILD-UP DURING THE REACTION WHICH CAUSED IT TO BURST OFF THE TRUCK FITTING AND SPRAY HIM IN THE UPPER CHEST AND FACE WITH THE LIQUID. ERIK RINSED HIS EYES THOROUGHLY AT THE EYE WASH STATION, AND JOE ALSO RINSED THEM OUT WITH BOTTLED SALINE SOLUTION. IT APPEARED THAT FIRST AID MEASURES HAD BEEN SUCCESSFUL IN FLUSHING THE MATERIAL FROM ERIK’S EYES, AND ERIK SAID HE WAS OK, BUT BECAUSE OF THE APPARENT REACTION AND CONSEQUENT UNKNOWN NATURE OF THE MATERIAL, I DECIDED TO TAKE ERIK TO THE HOSPITAL FOR FURTHER EVALUATION AND TREATMENT.  WE ARRIVED AT THE HOSPITAL AT APPROXIMATELY 10:00 AM. WHILE ERIK WAS RECEIVING TREATMENT I SPOKE WITH DAVID ARCHULETA, WHO HAD RETURNED TO THE PLANT. HE INFORMED ME THAT EMERGENCY PERSONNEL HAD TAKEN CONTROL OF THE SCENE, EVACUATING ALL PERSONNEL TO THE STOCKYARD PARKING LOT ACROSS THE RAILROAD TRACKS, AND THAT OUR PRESENCE THERE WAS REQUIRED THERE AFTER ERIK’S MEDICAL TREATMENT WAS DONE. WE ARRIVED THERE AT APPROXIMATELY 12:00 PM, WHERE WE WERE UPDATED BY KLAMATH COUNTY FIRE DISTRICT #1 CAPTAIN HELGE MCGEE AND OSP DEPUTY STATE FIRE MARSHAL SCOTT RICE. THEY INFORMED IS THAT THEIR STRATEGY WAS TO WATCH FROM A DISTANCE WITH A SPOTTING SCOPE UNTIL THE TRUCK HAD STOPPED OFF-GASSING, THEN TO TRY AND GET A HEAT READING ON THE TANK. WE WERE RELEASED TO GO GET LUNCH AND RETURNED TO THE SITE AT APPROXIMATELY 1:00 PM.  AFTER THE OFF-GASSING STOPPED AND A COUPLE OF HEAT READINGS WERE TAKEN BY EMERGENCY PERSONNEL, WE WERE INFORMED THAT THEY FELT THE REACTION WAS STABILIZED TO THE POINT WHERE THEY FELT IT WAS SAFE TO TRY AND RETRIEVE A SAMPLE OF THE MATERIAL. WE DIRECTED THEM TO THE LOCATION OF THE DRIVERS CUSTOMER RETAIN A SAMPLE IN THE PLANT (THERE WAS ONLY ONE STOP DONE WITH THE TRCUK THAT DAY), WHICH THEY RETRIEVED AND BEGAN TESTING IN THEIR HAZMAT TRAILER. THE PRELIMINARY RESULTS WERE SHARED WITH US; PH 2 WITH THE PRESENCE OF SEVERAL CHEMICALS CONSISTENT WITH USED OIL (SEE CEDAR POINT NURSERY DRIVERS RETAIN SAMPLE PHOTO). WE WERE TOLD THAT WE NEEDED TO M

column168: ON MONDAY, AUGUST 20, 2018 RAILROAD PERSONNEL IDENTIFIED A LEAK ON A TANK CAR (GATX 12589) IN THE VALDOSTA YARD. VR PERSONNEL RESPONDED TO THE LEAK AND BEGAN ANALYZING THE CAR FOR THE SOURCE OF THE POTENTIAL LEAK. UPON DETERMINING THE RELEASE HAD HIT THE BALLAST IN THE VICINITY OF THE TRACKS, THE GEORGIA DEPARTMENT OG NATURAL RESOURCES (GA DNR) WAS NOTIFIED AT APPROXIMATELY 13:30 AND CASE NUMBER 87220 WAS ASSIGNED. THE RELEASE WAS DETERMINED TO BE ETHEPHON WHICH IS HERBICIDE (GROWTH REGULATOR) WITH AN ACID BASE, THE SDS FOR THE PRODUCTS INCLUDED IN ATTACHMENT A. FOLLOWING THE CALL THE GA DNR, VR PERSONNEL CALLED HULL'S ENVIRONMENT (HULL'S) TO RESPOND TO ASSIST IN CLEANING UP THE RELEASE AND SECURING THE PRODUCT FOR TRANSFER. THE NRC WAS NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE AT APPROXIMATELY 15:20 AND INCIDENT REPORT #1222155 WAS ASSIGNED. APPROXIMATELY 60 GALLONS ARE BELIEVED TO HAVE BEEN RELEASED FROM THE 16,000 GALLON CAR. NO WATERBODIES WERE IMPACTED BY THE RELEASE. VR PERSONNEL PLACED CATCH PANS UNDERNEATH THE LEAKING AREA AT APPROXIMATELY 14:00 TO CAPTURE PRODUCT. HULLS ARRIVED ONSITE AT APPROXIMATELY 17:00 AND DEPLOYED BOOM AROUND THE IMPACTED AREA AND CHEMICAL PADS TO CAPTURE FREE PRODUCT. POTASH WAS ALSO APPLIED TO THE AREA TO NEUTRALIZE THE ACID BASE IF THE ETHEPHON, VR AND HULL'S PERSONNEL PROBED THE CAR TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK AND ULTIMATELY DETERMINED THAT CORROSION OF THE INNER TANK HAD LEADING TO THE RELEASE. THE POINT OF RELEASE WAS IDENTIFIED AROUND 20:30 AND WAS PLUGGED WITH A WOODEN PLUG AND LIQUID METAL. ONCE IT WAS DETERMINED THE CAR WAS NO LONGER LEAKING, IT WAS MOVED APPROXIMATELY 100 FEET WEST ON TRACK 1 TO ASSIST WITH THE PRODUCT TRANSFER. AN EMPTY TANK CARE (GATX 12583) FITTING THE PROPER SPECIFICATIONS TO HOLD THE ETHEPHON WAS BROUGHT INTO THE VALDOSTA YARD AND STAGED AT APPROXIMATELY 06:00 ON TUESDAY , AUGUST 21, 2018. HULL'S ACQUIRED THE PROPER TRANSFER HOSES AND FITTINGS AND BEGAN TRANSFER OPERATIONS AT APPROXIMATELY 10:30 AND ENDED APPROXIMATELY 16:00. HULL'S REMOVED IMPACTED BALLAST FROM THE AREA OF THE RELEASE UTILIZING A VACUUM EXTRACTION TRUCK. THE INTENT IS TO REMOVE THE IMPACTED BALLAST TO THE BOTTOM OF THE TIES OR TO THE EXTENT OF VISIBLE IMPACTS, WHICHEVER OCCURS FIRST. IMPACTED BALLAST WILL BE SEGREGATED AND STAGED ON POLY IN A ROLL OFF FOR FUTURE DISPOSAL AT AN APPROVED FACILITY. VACUUM EXTRACTION BEGAN AT APPROXIMATELY 13:00. THE AREA WHERE BALLAST WAS REMOVED WILL BE DOCUMENTED AND BACKFILLED FOR SAFETY.

column168: On 8/14/2018 at approximately 11:15 CST, WA UTC Inspector found the SHPX 208465 to be leaking slightly through a closed BOV cap.  Due to proximity to the receiving facility (destination) and the minor release, it was allowed to be placed at the facility for containment and offloading.  BNSF worked with WAUTC inspector and the receiving facility to provide information from the release.  The destination indicated that upon inspection, they noticed a minor leak (few drips per minute) coming from the threads.  They worked to offload the car and removed the cap to determine the integrity of the BOV.  While in the closed position, the BOV had minor seepage past the ball.  The gasket appeared to be in good condition in the cap and workers reported that it was tool tight when they removed the cap.  The shipper was notified to obtain an OTMA for movement from the facility prior to offering back into transportation.

column168: ON 29TH AUGUST AT APPROXIMATELY 08:30AM AT THE LINDE CUSTOMER VERIDIAM SITE IN EL CAJON, CALIFORNIA A LIQUID HYDROGEN TANKER WAS MAKING A TRANSFER OF PRODUCT WHEN A FIRE STARTED AT THE TANKER VENT STACK DURING POST-DELIVERY VENTING. THE EMERGENCY SERVICES WERE CALLED – FIRE ENGINES FROM TWO STATIONS ATTENDED. THE FACILITY, LOCAL SCHOOLS AND BUSINESSES WERE EVACUATED AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE. THE FIRE WAS ISOLATED TO THE TANKER VENT STACK. SAN DIEGO COUNTY HAZARDOUS MATERIAL INCIDENT TEAM PERSONNEL CLOSED THE VENT VALVE AND FIRE WAS EXTINGUISHED AT APPROXIMATELY 11:00 AM. THERE WERE NO RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DUE CONSUMPTION BY FIRE. THERE WERE NO REPORTED INJURIES OR DAMAGE TO PROPERTY. THE REAR OF THE TANKER DID INCURRED SOME MINOR FIRE DAMAGE. THE TANKER WAS INSPECTED AND RELEASED TO LINDE BY SAN DIEGO CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT, SAN DIEGO COUNTY HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INCIDENT TEAM AND CALIFORNIA HIGHWAY PATROL AT APPROXIMATELY 1:30 PM. TANKER WAS TRANSPORTED SAFELY BACK TO LINDE’S PLANT AT CITY OF INDUSTRY, CALIFORNIA. THE TANKER WAS TRANSPORTED TO A 3RD PARTY VENDOR FOR INSPECTION. AN INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINATION ROOT CAUSE(S) FOR IGNITION OF THE HYDROGEN DURING ROUTINE VENTING IS IN PROGRESS. PRELIMINARY FINDINGS ARE THAT A VALVE FAILED AND SOME OF THE VALVE SEAT MATERIAL, ALONG WITH A POTENTIAL LACK OF PROPER GROUNDING AT THE TIME OF THE VENTING CONTRIBUTED TO THE IGNITION THROUGH STATIC BUILD-UP.
column169: A REVIEW OF ALL VENT STACKS ON ALL LINDE HYDROGEN TRAILERS IS UNDERWAY TO DETERMINE IF THERE ARE SIMILAR VALVES IN USE. SUCH VALVES USE WILL BE REVIEWED TO DETERMINE SUITABILITY. PROPER GROUNDING PROCEDURES WILL BE REVIEWED WILL ALL DRIVERS TO ENSURE THAT PRIOR TO ANY VENTING, BODING OF THE TANKER TO EARTH TO PREVENT STATIC SPARKS IS ASSURED.

column168: ON 29TH AUGUST AT APPROXIMATELY 08:30 AM AT THE LINDE CUSTOMER VERIDIAM SITE IN EL CAJON, CALIFORNIA A LIQUID HYDROGEN TANKER WAS MAKING A TRANSFER OF PRODUCT WHEN A FIRE STARTED AT THE TANKER VENT STACK DURING POST-DELIVERY VENTING. THE EMERGENCY SERVICES WERE CALLED - FIRE ENGINES FROM TWO STATIONS ATTENDED. THE FACILITY, LOCAL SCHOOLS AND BUSINESSES WERE EVACUATED AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE. THE FIRE WAS ISOLATED TO THE TANKER VENT STACK. SAN DIEGO COUNTY HAZARDOUS MATERIAL INCIDENT TEAM PERSONNEL CLOSED THE VENT VALVE AND FIRE WAS EXTINGUISHED AT APPROXIMATELY 11:00 AM. THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DUE CONSUMPTION BY FIRE. THERE WERE NO REPORTED INJURIES OR DAMAGE TO PROPERTY. THE REAR OF THE TANKER DID INCURRED SOME MINOR FIRE DAMAGE. THE TANKER WAS INSPECTED AND RELEASED TO LINDE BY SAN DIEGO CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT, SAN DIEGO DEIGO COUNTY HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INCIDENT TEAM AND CALIFORNIA HIGHWAY PATROL AT APPROXIMATELY 1:30 PM. TANKER WAS TRANSPORTED SAFELY BACK TO LINE'S PLANT AT CITY OF INDUSTRY, CALIFORNIA. THE TANKER WAS TRANSPORTED TO A 3RD PARTY VENDOR FOR INSPECTION. AN INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINATION ROOT CAUSE(S) FOR IGNITION OF THE HYDROGEN DURING ROUTINE VENTING IS IN PROGRESS. PRELIMINARY FINDINGS ARE THAT A VALVE FAILED AND SOME OF THE VALVE SEAT MATERIAL, ALONG WITH A POTENTIAL LACK OF PROPER GROUNDING AT THE TIME OF THE VENTING CONTRIBUTED TO THE IGNITION THOUGH STATIC BUILD-UP.
column169: A REVIEW OF ALL VENT STACKS ON ALL LINDE HYDROGEN TRAILERS IS UNDERWAY TO DETERMINE IF THERE ARE SIMILAR VALVES IN USE. SUCH VALVES USE WILL BE REVIEWED TO DETERMINE SUITABILITY. PROPER GROUNDING PROCEDURES WILL BE REVIEWED WITH ALL DRIVERS TO ENSURE THAT PRIOR TO ANY VENTING, BODING OF THE TANKER TO EARTH TO PREVENT STATIC SPARKS IS ASSURED.

column168: ON 23 AUGUST 2018, AT 2321 HOURS A VEHICLE ACCIDENT OCCURRED AT MILE POST 382.5 ON THE DALTON HIGHWAY, RESULTING IN ROLLOVER OF A FUEL TANKER CARRYING 9,716 GALLONS OF ULTRA-LOW SULFUR DIESEL (ULSD) AND THE DEATH OF THE DRIVER. THE FORWARD PORTION OF THE TANKER WAS TORN DURING IMPACT WHERE SOME LEAKAGE OCCURRED. THERE WAS ALSO LEAKAGE FROM THE DOME LIDS, SINCE THE TANKER WAS LAYING ON IT'S SIDE. RESPONSE ACTIONS INCLUDED: REMOVING REMAINING FUEL FROM TANKER, DEPLOYING SORBENTS/BOOM, AND CAPTURING FUEL IN BUCKETS. INITIAL RESPONSE TIME OF PERSONNEL OCCURRED APPROXIMATELY 2 HOURS FOLLOWING TIME OF ACCIDENT (2321 HRS.) SEE ULSD INVENTORY DETAILS BELOW:  ORIGINAL VOLUME OF ULSD IN TANKER: 9,716 GALLONS ULSD RECOVERED FROM TANKER: 7,937 GALLONS ULSD SPILLED 9,716-7,937 = 1,779 GALLONS ULSD RECOVERED FROM SEPARATION TANK: 1,413 GALLONS ULSD RECOVERED FROM ABORBS: 93 GALLONS TOTAL VOLUME SPILLED: 9,716-1,413-93= 273 GALLONS  COORDINATION EFFORTS ARE ON-GOING AT THE SITE. REMOVAL OF CONTAMINATED SOIL AND INTEGRITY INSPECTION OF GAS PIPELINE AND FIBER OPTIC CABLES ARE CURRENTLY IN-WORK. COST OF RE-MEDIATION ARE UNKNOWN AT THIS TIME, BUT CAN BE PROVIDED ONCE CLEAN-UP EFFORTS ARE COMPLETE.
column169: LISTED BELOW ARE SOME CORRECTIVE ACTIONS/IMPROVEMENTS COLVILLE IS ACTIVELY WORKING:  1. INSTALLATION OF DOME LID CLAMPS FOR DOME LIDS ON THE TRANSPORT TANKER FLEET. DURING THE ROLLOVER, SOME OF THE ULSD DID SEEP OUT OF THE DOME LIDS, HOWEVER NONE OF THE DOME LIDS ACTUALLY FAILED. COLVILLE BELIEVES THAT DOME LID CLAMPS WOULD HAVE REDUCED LEAKAGE BY USING THESE DEVICES.  2. ACTIVE PARTICIPANTS AND HIGHLY ENGAGED WITH THE HAUL ROAD SAFETY GROUP (DALTON HIGHWAY) TO EXCHANGE ROAD AWARENESS INFORMATION  3. THE ROAD SURFACE OF THE DALTON HIGHWAY ALONG MP 382.5 WAS CONTRIBUTING FACTOR TO THE ACCIDENT. COLVILLE IS ACTIVELY ENGAGED WITH DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION AND DEDICATED WITH IMPROVING THE DALTON HIGHWAY, ALONG WITH INCREASED AWARENESS TO DRIVERS OF ROAD CONDITIONS.

column168: MPCA WAS NOTIFIED AT 7:30 PM BY AZ DOT HAZMAT ON ROLLOVER OF CONTAINER CAMU212424-8 WHILE GOING WESTBOUND ON I-10 MILE POST 331. DRIVER STATED TO DPS TROOPER HE SWERVED TO AVOID REAR ENDING A VEHICLE AHEAD OF HIM AND LOST CONTROL OF THE TANK CAUSING IT TO ROLLOVER ON IT'S SIDE. INITIAL REPORT OF LIQUID OUT OF THE TANK WAS APPROXIMATELY 200 GAL. MPCA NOTIFIED NRC OF POTENTIAL LEAKAGE. FURTHER INFORMATION WAS RECEIVED FROM THE SCENE AT 9:03 PM THE LEAKAGE HAD STOPPED AND THE TANK WOULD BE SAFELY UP RIGHTED AND COULD BE SAFELY TOWED TO A SECURE YARD FOR EVALUATION. MPCA PERSONNEL TRAVELED TO THE SITE ON SEPT 4TH TO ASSES THE ROAD WORTHINESS OF THE TANK INSURING THE INTEGRITY OF THE TANK TO TRANSPORT TO MPCA. THE TEAM ASSESSED THE CONDITION OF THE TANK AS ACCEPTABLE. THE TANK WAS TRANSPORTED BACK TO MPCA IN MESA WHERE THE TANK WAS WEIGHED AND MATERIAL WAS TESTED. THE TANK WAS EMPTIED OUT ESTIMATED AT THE SCENE OF 200 GALLONS. NRC WAS NOTIFIED OF THE WEIGHT DIFFERENCE BY MPCA. SUSPECTED CAUSE OF THE ROLLOVER IS DISTRACTED DRIVER.

column162: DIRECTOR, HAZ MAT FIELD OPS & ER
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1125 CT, H BARLAC1 20 DERAILED 16 CARS (15 ON THEIR SIDES) BETWEEN VERDEMONT AND KEENBROOK. THE TRAIN WAS OPERATING ON MAIN 3 AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT. THE UTLX 201919 SUSTAINED A SMALL PUNCTURE ON THE HEAD OF THE CAR NEAR THE STUB SILL. THIS SMALL PUNCTURE RESULTED IN THE LOSS OF APPROXIMATELY 200-500 GALLONS OF NAPHTHA FROM THE CAR. BNSF AND CONTRACT RESPONDERS WERE ABLE TO PLACE CONTAINMENT UNDER THE LEAK AND PLACE A PLUG IN THE HOLE, STOPPING THE RELEASE. THE REMAINING CONTENTS WERE TRANSFERRED BY VACUUM TRUCK TO AN TEMPORARY STORAGE TANK FOR FUTURE HANDLING. IMPACTS TO THE SOIL WERE ADDRESSED BY REMOVAL OF IMPACTED SOIL AND STOCKPILING FOR FUTURE CHARACTERIZATION AND DISPOSAL.

column14: 14 MILES WEST OF BIG LAKE, TX
column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: ON AUGUST 15, 2018, EMPLOYEE WAS DRIVING ON US HWY 67 EAST, TRANSPORTING 60 LEAD ACID BATTERIES ON A FLATBED TRAILER FROM AEP'S RIO PECOS SUBSTATION LOCATED NEAR GIRVIN, TX TO THE AEP SAN ANGELO TRANSMISSION SERVICE CENTER LOCATED IN SAN ANGELO, TX. THE BATTERIES WERE TRANSPORTED UNDER THE PROVISIONS OF 49 CFR 173.159(E). AT 5:00 PM THE DRIVER STOPPED TO CHECK THE LOAD IN RANKIN, TX AND EVERYTHING WAS INTACT. HE PROCEEDED ON HIS WAY AND AT 5:30 PM HE STOPPED TO CHECK HIS LOAD AGAIN IN BIG LAKE, TX AND NOTICED THAT ONE EXIDE EA9 BATTERY WAS MISSING. AT 5:35 PM EMPLOYEE'S SUPERVISOR CALLED AEP ENVIRONMENTAL TO SEEK ADVICE. ENVIRONMENTAL ADVISED THAT THE EMPLOYEE SHOULD RETRACE HIS ROUTE TO LOOK FOR THE LOST BATTERY. ONCE THE DRIVER OBSERVED A BATTERY WAS MISSING HE RE-STRAPPED THE LOAD PRIOR TO RESUMING HIS TRIP. AT 7:00 PM THE EMPLOYEE COMPLETED HIS SEARCH AND FOUND THE CARCASS OF THE BATTERY ON THE DIRT ON THE SOUTH SIDE OF US HWY 67, APPROXIMATELY 14 MILES WEST OF BIG LAKE, TX. THE CASE WAS BROKEN IN TWO PIECES AND ALL OF THE SULFURIC ACID HAD ESCAPED. THIS TYPE OF BATTERY 1.7 GALLONS OF ELECTROLYTE. NO VISIBLE TRACES OF CONTAMINATION WERE APPARENT. THE DRIVER PLACED THE BATTERY REMNANTS IN A SEALED PLASTIC BAG AND RETURNED IT TO THE AEP SAN ANGELO TRANSMISSION YARD. IT IS NOW STORED IN A PLASTIC BAG INSIDE OF A STEEL DRUM PENDING DISPOSAL. A POST-INCIDENT INVESTIGATION SHOWED THAT A STRAP AROUND A GROUP OF BATTERIES ON A  WOODEN PALLET HAD LOOSENED DURING TRANSPORT ALLOWING ONE OF THE BATTERIES TO FALL FROM THE TRAILER.
column169: TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT, AEP WILL GATHER INFORMATION FROM OTHER EMPLOYEES WHO TRANSPORT BATTERIES TO IDENTIFY BEST PRACTICES FOR SECURING THE LOAD. IN THE FUTURE BATTERIES PLACED ON WOODEN PALLETS COULD BE BETTER SECURED WITH MORE STRAPS OR THE USE OF CELLOPHANE MATERIAL TO WRAP THE ENTIRE LOAD. WOODEN BOXES ARE SOMETIMES AVAILABLE TO PLACE BATTERIES INSIDE OF PRIOR TO TRANSPORT. ONCE IDEAS ARE GATHERED, ADDITIONAL TRAINING WILL BE OFFERED TO ALL EMPLOYEES WHO TRANSPORT BATTERIES.
