column168: UNITED PUMPING SERVICE, INC. (UPS) DRIVER LOADED 12 TOTES HOLDING 3,600 GALLONS OF NON RCRA HAZARDOUS WASTE LIQUID FROM CROSBY & OVERTON INTO A UPS VEHICLE (DRY VAN). THE TOTES WERE THEN TRANSPORTED TO VEOLIA'S DISPOSAL FACILITY IN AZUSA, CA. WHEN THE DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE FACILITY IT WAS NOTICED THAT DURING TRANSIT 3 OF THE 12 TOTES HAD CAPS THAT WERE NOT PROPERLY SEALED WHICH THEN CAUSED SOME OF THE LIQUID (2 QUARTS) TO SPILL ONTO THE VEHICLE FLOOR. THE UPS DRIVER ALERTED A VEOLIA EMPLOYEE AND THE UPS DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP THE SPILL.  CROSBY & OVERTON PERSONNEL AND UNITED PUMPING SERVICE, INC. PERSONNEL FAILED TO MAKE SURE THAT ALL CAPS WERE PROPERLY CLOSED ON THE TOTES WHICH RESULTED IN SPILLAGE IN THE VEHICLE. NO MATERIAL HIT THE OUTSIDE GROUND AND ONLY AFFECTED THE INSIDE OF THE DRY VAN.
column169: CROSBY & OVERTON WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT. THEY WERE ASKED TO PLEASE MAKE SURE THEIR EMPLOYEES ARE REMINDED TO MAKE SURE ALL SHIPMENTS ARE SEALED AND READY FOR TRANSIT. UNITED PUMPING SERVICE, INC. PERSONNEL WERE ALSO REMINDED TO MAKE SURE ALL LIDS AND CAPS ARE PROPERLY SEALED BEFORE TRANSIT TO PREVENT ANOTHER INCIDENT.

column168: WE WERE NOTIFIED BY FRA AND PUCO INSPECTORS THAT WE HAD ACFX 220342 A RESIDUE CAR IN OUR INBOUND YARD THAT HAD A LEAKING VALVE. WE MOVED THE CAR TO A TRACK TO BE REPAIRED. UTLX WAS NOTIFIED TO COME AND REPAIR/CLOSE THE VALVE. THE CAR WAS REPAIRED ON 9-18-18.
column169: THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AS WELL AS THE DESTINATION FACILITY. WE INFORMED THEM OF THE VALVE ISSUE AND TOLD THEM TO MAKE SURE ALL VALVES ARE CLOSED AND NOT LEAKING BEFORE SHIPMENT.

column168: ON 8/30/2018 AT APPROXIMATELY 01:00 GRS, REPORTING DGO RECEIVED A CALL FROM DGO KEN COLLINS REFERENCE A POSSIBLE LEAK FROM TANK CAR CGTX26100 (L-UN2055 STYRENE).  CN RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED FINDING VAPOR EMITTING FROM THE A-R UNDERSIDE OF THE TANK AT A BREAK IN THE JACKET WELD. COMBUSTIBLE GAS METER (CGM) READINGS WERE BETWEEN 50-80 PPM VOC EMITTING FROM THE BREAK. CN RESPONSE TEAM PATCHED THE BREAK INT HE WELD SEAM, PREVENTING VAPORS FROM ESCAPING FURTHER. POST PATCH, NO DETECTABLE VAPORS WERE IDENTIFIED USING THE CGM.  CAR WAS OFFLOADED AND CLEANED/PURGED THE SAME DAY WITH A HOLE MEASURING APPROXIMATELY 18" X 18" CUT INTO THE JACKET TO INSPECT THE TANK. INSULATION REMOVED FROM THE CUT HOLE YIELDED EVIDENCE OF STYRENE CONTAMINATION.  CGTX 26100 WAS SENT TO HOMESHOP FOR REPAIR. RECEIVING CAR PROX 23236 WAS FORWARDED TO THE COSIGNEE OF CGTX 26100.

column168: DRIVER WAS IN ROUTE TO DELIVER LOCATION DURING RUSH HOUR TRAFFIC. TO AVOID A POTENTIAL ACCIDENT THE WAS FORCED TO BRAKE HARD. A VEHICLE CAME ACROSS TWO LANES TO EXIT THE ROADWAY ON THE RIGHT FORCING OUR DRIVER TO COME TO A SUDDEN STOP. THE LOAD WAS SPLIT (NOSE AND REAR) TO EQUALLY DISTRIBUTE THE WEIGHT. IN ADDITION, IT WAS ALSO SEGREGATED IN THE TRAILER TO COMPLY WITH DOT TRANSPORTATION REQUIREMENTS. THE SUDDEN STOP CAUSED THE MATERIAL IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER TO SHIFT FORWARD AND CRASH INTO DRUMS ON THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.(ONLY 1 LOAD BAR) THIS CAUSED THE VALVE ON THE IBC TO BREAK OFF WHICH RESULTED IN APPROXIMATELY 30 GALLONS LEAKING ONTO THE FLOOR. THE TRAILER IS EQUIPPED WITH A STEEL FLOOR TO CONTAIN HAZARDOUS RELEASES SO NOTHING LEAKED ONTO THE ROADWAY OR IMPACTED THE SOIL. CURA ENVIRONMENTAL WAS HIRED TO HANDLE CLEANUP AND OVER-PACK TOTE.
column169: AS A CORRECTIVE ACTION VEOLIA HAS AGREED TO USE MULTIPLE LOAD BARS AND / OR STRAPS TO SECURE SPLIT LOADS. IN ADDITION, ALL BULK CONTAINERS WILL BE TRANSPORTED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1125 CT, H BARLAC1 20 DERAILED 16 CARS (15 ON THEIR SIDES) BETWEEN VERDEMONT AND KEENBROOK. THE TRAIN WAS OPERATING ON MAIN 3 AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT. THE UTLX 201919 SUSTAINED A SMALL PUNCTURE ON THE HEAD OF THE CAR NEAR THE STUB SILL. THIS SMALL PUNCTURE RESULTED IN THE LOSS OF APPROXIMATELY 200-500 GALLONS OF NAPHTHA FROM THE CAR. BNSF AND CONTRACT RESPONDERS WERE ABLE TO PLACE CONTAINMENT UNDER THE LEAK AND PLACE A PLUG IN THE HOLE, STOPPING THE RELEASE. THE REMAINING CONTENTS WERE TRANSFERRED BY VACUUM TRUCK TO AN TEMPORARY STORAGE TANK FOR FUTURE HANDLING. IMPACTS TO THE SOIL WERE ADDRESSED BY REMOVAL OF IMPACTED SOIL AND STOCKPILING FOR FUTURE CHARACTERIZATION AND DISPOSAL

column168: ON 8/13/2018 AT APPROXIMATELY 13:30 HOURS, THE RUST & SONS TRUCK WAS EAST BOUND ON CA HWY 192 GOING DOWN HILL GOING INTO DEATH VALLEY AND THE BRAKES CAUGHT ON FIRE. THE DRIVER PULLED OVER JUST WEST OF STOVEPIPE WELLS AND TRIED TO PUT THE FIRE OUT AND WAS UNSUCCESSFUL. HE THEN TRIED TO UN-HOOK THE TRACTOR FROM THE TRAILER AND AGAIN WAS UNSUCCESSFUL. THE CHP ARRIVED AND TOLD THE DRIVER TO GET AWAY FROM THE TRUCK AND STAY AWAY. THE TRUCK, TRAILER AND CONTENTS COMPLETELY BURNED.
column169: WHEN RUST & SONS DRIVERS ARE DISPATCHED, SAFETY IS FIRST AND FOREMOST. WHEN THE TRUCK IS FINISHED BEING LOADED AND THE DRIVER IS READY TO START THE HAUL THE DISPATCHER ASKS THE DRIVER A SERIES OF QUESTIONS. THE QUESTIONS INCLUDE "IS THE LOAD SECURE AND PROPERLY LOADED?", "IS THE PAPERWORK CORRECT AND COMPLETE?", "ARE THE PLACARDS THE CORRECT PLACARDS AND PROPERLY PLACED ON THE FRONT, REAR AND BOTH SIDES OF THE TRAILER?". THE DRIVER IS ALSO ASKED "DO YOU HAVE ENOUGH HOURS OF SERVICE TO LEGALLY COMPLETE THE TRIP? AND "DO YOU HAVE CONCERN ABOUT THE MECHANICAL CONDITION OF THE TRUCK AND TRAILER?", " THE ROUTE IS......AND THE FUEL STOPS ARE...... THEN THE DRIVER IS INSTRUCTED TO PLACE ALL OF THE PAPERWORK RELATED TO THE LOAD INTO THE PERMIT BOOK ALONG WITH THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDE BOOK AND THEN PLACE IT IN THE DOOR POCKET IN THE DRIVERS DOOR. THIS CONVERSATION TAKES PLACE WITH EVERY DRIVER ON EVERY LOAD AND DURING TRANSIT OF EVERY LOAD. THE DISPATCHER AND DRIVER FOR THIS LOAD HAD A DISCUSSION ABOUT THE ROUTE AND THE DRIVER DECIDED NOT TO TELL DISPATCH THAT HE WAS GOING ON A ROUTE NOT AUTHORIZED BY THE COMPANY. THE DRIVER WAS SUSPENDED FOR A WEEK AND DURING THAT WEEK RETRAINED ON DRIVING DOWN STEEP GRADES AND COACHED ON "HOW TO FOLLOW DIRECTIONS FROM HIS SUPERVISORS" AND REFRESHED ON HOW THE RUST & SONS "PROGRESSIVE DISCIPLINARY PLAN" WORKS. ANY VIOLATIONS DURING THE NEXT 12 MONTHS WILL RESULT IN EMPLOYMENT TERMINATION.

column168: On 8/14/2018 at approximately 11:15 CST, WA UTC Inspector found the SHPX 208465 to be leaking slightly through a closed BOV cap.  Due to proximity to the receiving facility (destination) and the minor release, it was allowed to be placed at the facility for containment and offloading.  BNSF worked with WAUTC inspector and the receiving facility to provide information from the release.  The destination indicated that upon inspection, they noticed a minor leak (few drips per minute) coming from the threads.  They worked to offload the car and removed the cap to determine the integrity of the BOV.  While in the closed position, the BOV had minor see page past the ball.  The gasket appeared to be in good condition in the cap and workers reported that it was tool tight when they removed the cap.  The shipper was notified to obtain an OTMA for movement from the facility prior to offering back into transportation.
column169: Shipper/car owner should review and ensure that gasket and valve maintenance programs are adequate to capture these defects prior to them occurring while in transportation.(NAR:579)

column168: On 12/06/18 at 1924 hours ET, Isabel De Toro from XPO Logistics, contacted ERTS in regard to a  hazardous release. This is located at Terminal LSX in San Antonio, TX. It was reported that on  08/31/18 at 0457 hours  (1) 5 gallon metal pail of FRC component  was damaged due to puncture  from a forklift blade. Approximately 1 cups released to the floor of  the concrete dock. Clean-up was  completed before ERTS notification. Damaged pail still needs to be over packed therefore ,ERTS  reviewed SDS with caller and caller expressed comfort in terminal personnel ability to successfully  overpack drum. Terminal personnel will place damaged pail into a 20 gallon poly drum and store into  facilities OS&D area.

column168: DIESEL FUEL AT THIS STATION HAS TO BE PUMPED INTO THEIR TANK. CARRIER TRAILER HAS TWO OUT LETS FOR PUMP OFFS. ONE OUT-LET ON EACH SIDE OF TRAILER. AS CARRIER DRIVER WAS PUMPING DIESEL WITH ONE OUT LET THE CAR LOCK CAR'S ON THE OTHER OUT-LET VIBRATED LOOSE AND THE CAP CAME OFF. 15 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL SPILLED OUT ON TO A ASPHALT PARKING LOT.
column169: OUT-LET CAR LOCK EAR'S WERE REPLACED WITH LOCKING CAM EARS SO THEY WILL NEVER VIBRATE LOOSE.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: The shipment was discovered to have leaked when employees witnessed a wet box. Upon opening the box we found three round metal friction lid cans. All three cans had can clips vs ring locks for positive closure. The clips on one can failed allowing the friction lid to separate from the can allowing the spill to occur. In addition to the inappropriate Positive Closure, it appeared to me that the shipper used inner packaging that had not been tested with the UN POP box used. In addition to the paint cans was a rectangular plastic bottle& a round plastic jar, each containing other compatible hazmats. The shipment was held pending an FAA inspection. MEM SECFO Hazmat Manager Stan Satchell was notified electronically.
